"""
# Spec Plan — `common_compression_framework`

This planning spec replaces the subset contract with the full pure-Simple target.
The implementation work must convert the scenarios below into executable `describe` / `it`
coverage with real assertions in compiled mode.

Describe REQ-001 through REQ-008A: façade and API semantics
  Scenario REQ-001/REQ-002/REQ-006/REQ-007: `std.common.compress` round-trips LZ4, Zstd, and XZ/LZMA2 through the shared façade
    Given supported payload classes for each codec
    When callers use `compress_bytes` and `decompress_bytes`
    Then original payload bytes are restored and codec auto-detect or explicit hint behavior matches the request

  Scenario REQ-003/REQ-004: option fields affect real behavior rather than placeholders
    Given callers vary `level`, `checksum`, `content_size`, `block_mode`, `dictionary_bytes`, and `dictionary_id`
    When encoding is requested
    Then supported codecs emit and validate the corresponding framed behavior and unsupported combinations fail explicitly

  Scenario REQ-006A/REQ-008A/REQ-012: checked encode entrypoints preserve typed option failures
    Given invalid or unsupported option combinations
    When callers use `try_compress_bytes` or `encoder_finish_checked`
    Then the API returns typed `CompressionError.UnsupportedFeature` or other specific failures instead of silently normalizing the request

  Scenario REQ-006/REQ-006A/REQ-008/REQ-008A: fail-fast and checked streaming APIs stay aligned
    Given the same buffered input is encoded via single-shot and streaming entrypoints
    When checked and fail-fast wrappers are compared
    Then success outputs match byte-for-byte and failure behavior differs only in typed-result versus unwrap semantics

Describe REQ-009: full LZ4 coverage
  Scenario REQ-009A: raw LZ4 block decode requires an explicit codec hint
    Given a raw LZ4 block without frame magic
    When the caller passes `CompressionCodec.lz4`
    Then decode succeeds and auto-detect alone does not misclassify it

  Scenario REQ-009B: framed LZ4 supports multi-block payloads and frame flags
    Given LZ4 frames carrying block checksum, content checksum, and content size
    When the shared decoder and encoder process them
    Then payload bytes, checksums, and size metadata are preserved and verified

  Scenario REQ-009C: host interoperability holds for emitted and ingested frames
    Given host-generated standard LZ4 frames and Simple-generated frames
    When both directions are decoded by the opposite implementation
    Then payload bytes match exactly

  Scenario REQ-009D: LZ4 corruption fails closed with typed errors
    Given bad headers, malformed tokens, bad lengths, checksum mismatches, and truncation
    When decoding runs
    Then `CompressionError` reports a typed failure instead of partial or normalized output

Describe REQ-010: full Zstd coverage
  Scenario REQ-010A: normal host-generated frame variants decode successfully
    Given Zstd frames covering frame-header variants, window/content-size combinations, raw blocks, RLE blocks, compressed blocks, repeated FSE tables, compressed Huffman weights, treeless literals, and 4-stream literals
    When `common.compress` decodes them
    Then the original payload is restored and frame constraints are validated

  Scenario REQ-010B: the pure-Simple encoder emits interoperable standard frames
    Given small, medium, large, repetitive, incompressible, and mixed payloads
    When the Simple encoder emits Zstd frames
    Then host `zstd` decodes them successfully and content checksum/content size fields validate

  Scenario REQ-010C: framed dictionary support honors both dictionary bytes and dictionary id
    Given matching and mismatching `dictionary_bytes` plus `dictionary_id` combinations
    When encoding and decoding dictionary-backed frames
    Then matching inputs round-trip and invalid dictionary metadata fails explicitly

  Scenario REQ-010D: multi-block, multi-frame, corruption, and truncation paths fail truthfully
    Given concatenated or repeated Zstd frame content plus malformed entropy tables, bad checksums, impossible sizes, and truncated inputs
    When decoding runs
    Then results are either successful full restoration or the correct typed failure category

Describe REQ-011: full XZ/LZMA2 coverage
  Scenario REQ-011A: LZMA2 compressed chunks decode successfully inside `.xz`
    Given host-generated and Simple-generated `.xz` streams using the LZMA2-only filter chain
    When decoding runs
    Then compressed chunks, not only uncompressed passthrough chunks, restore the original payload

  Scenario REQ-011B: `.xz` container validation covers block, index, footer, CRC, and concatenation behavior
    Given multi-block streams, concatenated streams, and valid CRC-protected metadata
    When the shared decoder processes the stream
    Then all blocks are restored in order and integrity checks are enforced

  Scenario REQ-011C: the pure-Simple encoder emits canonical `.xz` streams for host decode
    Given representative payload classes
    When the Simple encoder emits `.xz`
    Then host `xz` decodes the output and the payload bytes match exactly

  Scenario REQ-011D: unsupported filter chains and malformed tails fail explicitly
    Given non-LZMA2 filter chains, bad index/footer tails, bad CRCs, and truncation
    When decoding runs
    Then the API reports `UnsupportedFeature`, `InvalidHeader`, `ChecksumMismatch`, `TruncatedInput`, or `CorruptStream` as appropriate

Describe REQ-013: kernel adapter parity
  Scenario REQ-013A: kernel Zstd adapter matches shared decoder output
    Given valid Zstd frames from the common fixture matrix
    When both the kernel adapter and `common.compress` decode them
    Then returned payload bytes are identical

  Scenario REQ-013B: kernel adapter preserves its legacy error contract while delegating to `common.compress`
    Given invalid Zstd inputs covering every relevant typed compression failure
    When the kernel adapter is called
    Then it translates the shared `CompressionError` result into the expected `Result<[u8], text>` failure text deterministically

Describe REQ-014: shared-helper and forced-tier parity
  Scenario REQ-014A: scalar, AVX2, and NEON helper paths produce identical checksum and copy results
    Given shared helper inputs for CRC32, XXH32, match extension, literal copy, and overlap-safe match copy
    When each forced tier is called directly
    Then helper outputs match the scalar oracle exactly

  Scenario REQ-014B: codec behavior remains byte-for-byte identical across forced tiers
    Given the same representative payloads and codec options
    When encode and decode operations are forced through scalar, AVX2, and NEON helper seams
    Then compressed outputs and restored payloads remain identical across tiers

Describe corruption matrices across REQ-005/REQ-009/REQ-010/REQ-011/REQ-012
  Scenario CORR-001: bad header and magic handling
  Scenario CORR-002: truncated block, frame, index, and footer tails
  Scenario CORR-003: checksum corruption for LZ4, Zstd, and XZ structures
  Scenario CORR-004: malformed LZ4 token and length state
  Scenario CORR-005: malformed Zstd entropy tables and invalid dictionary metadata
  Scenario CORR-006: unsupported XZ filter chain metadata
  Scenario CORR-007: size-limit and impossible content-size failures

Implementation note
  The finished executable spec should group these scenarios into `describe` blocks per requirement family,
  use deterministic fixtures, and assert typed success and failure results without subset-only caveats.
"""
